english:
  title: Departing from Sangju
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The stubborn dawn star still flickers in the sky,
    I rise with the magpies' call.
    My wanderer's heart, dulled by thin wine,
    Flinches at the cold lamp's glare through fevered eyes.
    My traveling clothes hang loose as an old villager's,
    My packed belongings ragged as a mountain monk's.
    Though I long to return to my fields, I cannot—
    The ache of yearning for the capital won't release me.
    I shame Ko Pong, who fled the world entire;
    I fall short even of Ji Ying, who reads the seasons.
    Dew weighs heavy; my hat's brim droops and wilts,
    Wind cuts sharp; creases form along my sleeves.
    Frost still grips the stone paths ahead,
    Sunrise hasn't reached the cloud-veiled cliffs.
    Two streams of tears shed when I took leave of my parents
    Still wet my chest as dawn breaks over me.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Ko Pong (高鳳) was a recluse of the Later Han dynasty known for withdrawing from the world.
  - key: ''
    value: Ji Ying (季鷹) refers to Zhang Ziyuan, who could sense the coming of autumn seasons and left his post accordingly.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem contrasts the speaker's inability to achieve either the complete withdrawal of a recluse or the intuitive wisdom of those who know when to depart.
